% ============================================================
% ABSTRACT
% ============================================================
\begin{abstract}
Digital images can be manipulated in ways invisible to the human eye. Detecting such tampering and pinpointing exactly which pixels were altered is a critical challenge in image forensics. This report presents a systematic ablation study for pixel-level image tamper detection and localization on the CASIA~v2.0 benchmark dataset (12,614 images: 7,491 authentic + 5,123 tampered). The project explored four experimental lineages over 60+ controlled experiments, evolving from documentation-first planning through Kaggle notebook reproduction, research paper baseline recreation, and finally a pretrained UNet segmentation pipeline.

The final system uses a UNet encoder-decoder with a frozen ResNet-34 encoder (ImageNet pretrained), multi-quality Error Level Analysis (ELA) preprocessing, and CBAM attention modules. Through strict single-variable ablation (one change per experiment), we established that \textbf{input representation dominates all other factors}~--- switching from RGB to multi-quality RGB ELA (9-channel) was worth +34.19 percentage points (pp) in Pixel~F1, more than all other improvements combined. The best model achieves \textbf{Pixel~F1 = 0.7965}, \textbf{IoU = 0.6615}, and \textbf{Pixel~AUC = 0.9665}. The impact hierarchy is clear: \textbf{Input representation $>$ Attention mechanisms $>$ Training configuration $>$ Loss function}.
\end{abstract}

\textbf{Keywords:} Image tampering detection, image forgery localization, error level analysis, UNet segmentation, ablation study, CASIA dataset, CBAM attention.

% ============================================================
% 1. INTRODUCTION
% ============================================================
\section{Introduction}

Digital images are ubiquitous in journalism, law enforcement, scientific research, and social media. However, modern image editing tools such as Adobe Photoshop, GIMP, and AI-based inpainting make it easy to manipulate photographs in ways that are nearly undetectable by the human eye. Common types of tampering include:

\begin{itemize}[nosep]
    \item \textbf{Splicing:} Copying a region from one image and pasting it into another.
    \item \textbf{Copy-move:} Duplicating a part of an image within the same image, often to hide or fabricate content.
    \item \textbf{Inpainting:} Using AI algorithms to fill in or replace regions of an image.
\end{itemize}

The task of \textit{image forgery detection} (classifying an image as authentic or tampered) is useful, but \textit{image forgery localization} (producing a pixel-level mask of tampered regions) is far more valuable for forensic analysis. This project tackles both tasks simultaneously: given an input image, the system produces a binary mask highlighting tampered pixels, from which image-level classification is derived.

\subsection{Problem Formulation}

Given an input image $\mathbf{X} \in \mathbb{R}^{H \times W \times 3}$, the goal is to learn a mapping function $f_\theta$ that produces a pixel-level probability map:
\begin{equation}
    \hat{\mathbf{M}} = f_\theta(\mathbf{X}) \in [0, 1]^{H \times W}
\end{equation}
where $\hat{\mathbf{M}}_{i,j}$ represents the probability that pixel $(i,j)$ has been tampered with. The ground truth mask $\mathbf{M} \in \{0, 1\}^{H \times W}$ is a binary map where 1 indicates tampered pixels and 0 indicates authentic pixels.

Image-level classification is derived from the segmentation output:
\begin{equation}
    \hat{y} = \begin{cases} 1 & \text{if } \max_{i,j} \hat{\mathbf{M}}_{i,j} > \tau \\ 0 & \text{otherwise} \end{cases}
\end{equation}
where $\tau = 0.5$ is the binarization threshold.

\subsection{Challenges}

Building an effective tamper localization system faces several fundamental difficulties:

\begin{enumerate}[nosep]
    \item \textbf{Extreme pixel-level class imbalance:} Tampered regions often occupy less than 2\% of all pixels in an image. A model that predicts all pixels as authentic achieves $>$98\% pixel accuracy while being completely useless.
    \item \textbf{Forgery sophistication:} Skilled forgers adjust lighting, color balance, and compression to make edits blend seamlessly with surrounding content.
    \item \textbf{JPEG compression artifacts:} Re-saving images as JPEG introduces compression artifacts that can either mask tampering traces or create false forensic signals.
    \item \textbf{Small dataset size:} Forensic datasets like CASIA v2.0 contain only $\sim$12K images~--- orders of magnitude smaller than ImageNet's 1.2M images~\cite{deng2009imagenet}, making training from scratch impractical.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Contributions}

The key contributions of this work are:
\begin{enumerate}[nosep]
    \item A complete pipeline from raw images to pixel-level tamper localization using multi-quality ELA preprocessing and pretrained UNet segmentation.
    \item A rigorous ablation study across 60+ experiments establishing that \textbf{input representation dominates all other factors}.
    \item Transparent documentation of four research tracks, including three failed approaches whose lessons directly shaped the final system.
    \item Full reproducibility via Weights~\&~Biases~\cite{wandb2020} experiment tracking, fixed random seeds, and open-source code.
\end{enumerate}

% ============================================================
% 2. RELATED WORK
% ============================================================
\section{Related Work}

\subsection{Traditional Forensic Methods}

Early forgery detection relied on hand-crafted features. Error Level Analysis (ELA)~\cite{krawetz2007picture} re-saves an image at a given JPEG quality and measures the pixel-wise difference from the original; tampered regions show inconsistent compression residuals. JPEG block artifact analysis~\cite{bianchi2012jpeg} exploits the 8$\times$8 block structure of JPEG compression to detect re-compressed regions. Noise-based methods analyze local noise variance~--- tampered regions composited from different sources often have mismatched noise patterns. Color Filter Array (CFA) analysis detects inconsistencies in the Bayer pattern interpolation. While interpretable, these methods struggle with sophisticated forgeries and produce high false-positive rates when used in isolation.

\subsection{CNN-Based Classification}

Deep learning transformed forgery detection by learning features directly from data. Bayar and Stamm~\cite{bayar2018constrained} proposed constrained convolutional layers that suppress image content and learn manipulation-specific features. Nagm et al.~\cite{nagm2024etasr} combined ELA preprocessing with a custom CNN for binary classification (tampered vs.\ authentic), reporting 96.21\% accuracy on CASIA v2.0 (JPEG-only subset). However, classification-only models cannot localize tampered regions~--- they answer ``is it tampered?'' but not ``where?''

\subsection{Segmentation-Based Localization}

To achieve pixel-level localization, researchers adopted encoder-decoder architectures. The UNet~\cite{ronneberger2015unet}, originally designed for biomedical image segmentation, proved effective for tamper localization through its skip connections that preserve fine spatial details. UNet++~\cite{zhou2018unetplusplus} improved boundary delineation through nested dense skip connections. Using pretrained encoders (e.g., ResNet~\cite{he2016resnet} trained on ImageNet~\cite{deng2009imagenet}) significantly improves performance on small forensic datasets by providing rich, generalizable feature representations.

ManTra-Net~\cite{wu2019mantranet} introduced a self-supervised anomaly detection approach for forgery localization that generalizes across manipulation types without per-dataset fine-tuning. SPAN~\cite{hu2020span} used spatial pyramid attention to capture multi-scale manipulation traces for more precise boundary localization.

\subsection{Attention Mechanisms}

Attention modules help models focus on the most relevant features. SE-Net~\cite{hu2018senet} introduced channel attention through squeeze-and-excitation blocks. CBAM~\cite{woo2018cbam} extended this with both channel-wise and spatial attention, teaching the model which feature maps and spatial locations are most important. In our experiments, CBAM provided one of the most parameter-efficient improvements (+3.57pp Pixel F1 for only 11K parameters).

\subsection{Multi-Stream and Frequency-Domain Methods}

State-of-the-art systems combine multiple input streams. EMT-Net~\cite{emtnet2023} uses Swin Transformers with RGB, noise maps, and frequency features, achieving AUC=0.987 on NIST. SRM (Spatial Rich Model)~\cite{fridrich2012srm} high-pass filters extract manipulation traces in the noise domain. ObjectFormer~\cite{wang2022objectformer} uses transformer-based architectures that learn object-level relationships between image patches to detect manipulated regions. IF-OSN~\cite{wu2022ifosn} combines frequency-domain analysis with online social network compression patterns for robust detection even after social media re-compression.

These multi-stream methods represent the current frontier but require significantly more computational resources and training data. Our work demonstrates that substantial performance can be achieved with simpler architectures when the input representation is well-designed.

