\subsubsection{ELA Algorithm}

\begin{algorithm}[H]
\caption{Multi-Quality RGB ELA Computation}
\label{alg:ela}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\Require Input image $\mathbf{X}$, quality levels $\mathcal{Q} = \{75, 85, 95\}$
\Ensure 9-channel ELA tensor $\mathbf{X}_{\text{MQ-ELA}}$
\State $\text{channels} \gets [\,]$
\For{$Q \in \mathcal{Q}$}
    \State $\mathbf{X}_Q \gets \text{JPEG\_recompress}(\mathbf{X}, Q)$
    \State $\mathbf{D}_Q \gets |\mathbf{X} - \mathbf{X}_Q|$
    \State $s_Q \gets 255 \,/\, (\max(\mathbf{D}_Q) + \epsilon)$
    \State $\text{channels.append}(\mathbf{D}_Q \cdot s_Q)$ \Comment{3 RGB channels}
\EndFor
\State $\mathbf{X}_{\text{MQ-ELA}} \gets \text{concatenate}(\text{channels}, \text{axis}=\text{channel})$
\State \Return $\mathbf{X}_{\text{MQ-ELA}}$
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

\subsection{Model Architecture}

\subsubsection{UNet with ResNet-34 Encoder}

The model uses the Segmentation Models PyTorch (SMP) library's~\cite{yakubovskiy2019smp} UNet implementation with a ResNet-34~\cite{he2016resnet} encoder.

The ResNet-34 encoder uses residual connections:
\begin{equation}
    \mathbf{h}_l = \sigma(\mathbf{W}_l \ast \mathbf{h}_{l-1} + \mathbf{h}_{l-1})
\end{equation}
where $\ast$ denotes convolution, $\sigma$ is the activation function (ReLU), and the identity shortcut $\mathbf{h}_{l-1}$ allows gradients to flow directly through the network.

\textbf{Freeze strategy:} All encoder convolutional weights are frozen. Only BatchNorm layers remain unfrozen (trainable scale $\gamma$ and shift $\beta$ parameters). This allows BN statistics to adapt from ImageNet's natural image distribution to the ELA forensic domain:
\begin{equation}
    \hat{x} = \gamma \cdot \frac{x - \mu_{\text{batch}}}{\sqrt{\sigma^2_{\text{batch}} + \epsilon}} + \beta
\end{equation}

The first convolutional layer is modified to accept 9 input channels (from 3) by repeating the pretrained weights 3 times.

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{UNet Decoder Configuration}
\label{tab:decoder}
\begin{tabular}{c c c c}
\toprule
\textbf{Block} & \textbf{Channels} & \textbf{Input Scale} & \textbf{Skip From} \\
\midrule
1 & 256 & 1/16 & Encoder stage 4 \\
2 & 128 & 1/8 & Encoder stage 3 \\
3 & 64 & 1/4 & Encoder stage 2 \\
4 & 32 & 1/2 & Encoder stage 1 \\
5 & 16 & 1/1 & Input \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Model Parameter Summary}
\label{tab:params}
\begin{tabular}{l r r}
\toprule
\textbf{Component} & \textbf{Parameters} & \textbf{Trainable} \\
\midrule
Encoder (ResNet-34) & 21.3M & BN only \\
Decoder (5 blocks) & $\sim$3.17M & Yes \\
CBAM modules & 11,402 & Yes \\
Segmentation head & $\sim$1K & Yes \\
\midrule
\textbf{Total} & \textbf{24.4M} & \textbf{3.17M (13\%)} \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

This freeze strategy was validated empirically: P.2's aggressive unfreeze (23M trainable) overfit with a 1:2,615 data-to-parameter ratio. P.8's progressive unfreeze confirmed the best epoch occurred before any unfreezing stage.

\subsubsection{CBAM Attention Module}

CBAM~\cite{woo2018cbam} is injected into all 5 UNet decoder blocks. It applies two sequential attention operations:

\textbf{Channel Attention.} Given a feature map $\mathbf{F} \in \mathbb{R}^{C \times H \times W}$:
\begin{equation}
    \mathbf{M}_c(\mathbf{F}) = \sigma\!\Big(\text{MLP}\!\big(\text{AvgPool}(\mathbf{F})\big) + \text{MLP}\!\big(\text{MaxPool}(\mathbf{F})\big)\Big)
\end{equation}
where $\sigma$ is the sigmoid function and MLP is a shared two-layer network with bottleneck ratio $r=16$:
\begin{equation}
    \text{MLP}(\mathbf{z}) = \mathbf{W}_1 \cdot \text{ReLU}(\mathbf{W}_0 \cdot \mathbf{z})
\end{equation}
with $\mathbf{W}_0 \in \mathbb{R}^{C/r \times C}$ and $\mathbf{W}_1 \in \mathbb{R}^{C \times C/r}$.

\textbf{Spatial Attention.} After channel refinement $\mathbf{F}' = \mathbf{M}_c(\mathbf{F}) \otimes \mathbf{F}$:
\begin{equation}
    \mathbf{M}_s(\mathbf{F}') = \sigma\!\Big(f^{7 \times 7}\!\big([\text{AvgPool}_c(\mathbf{F}') \,;\, \text{MaxPool}_c(\mathbf{F}')]\big)\Big)
\end{equation}
where $f^{7 \times 7}$ is a $7 \times 7$ convolution and $[\cdot\,;\,\cdot]$ denotes concatenation along the channel axis. The final output is:
\begin{equation}
    \mathbf{F}'' = \mathbf{M}_s(\mathbf{F}') \otimes \mathbf{F}'
\end{equation}

